// const content = "<p>Alpine.js is a lightweight JavaScript framework used to build interactive front-end components. It&rsquo;s lean, easy-to-use, and harnesses the power of Vue&rsquo;s or React&rsquo;s interactivity, with the simplicity of using Tailwind CSS classes.</p> <div class=\"heading-wrapper level-h2\" tabindex=\"-1\"> <h2 id=\"what-is-alpinejs\">What is Alpine.js?</h2> </div> <p>Alpine.js is a minimal JavaScript framework for declarative programming. Unlike Vue or React, it doesn&rsquo;t require a build step and it works directly in your HTML. It is great for sprinkling in small bits of interactivity to HTML rendered on the server, like dropdowns, tabs, and modals.</p> <div class=\"heading-wrapper level-h2\" tabindex=\"-1\"> <h2 id=\"key-features-of-alpinejs\">Key Features of Alpine.js</h2> </div> <div class=\"heading-wrapper level-h3\" tabindex=\"-1\"> <h3 id=\"lightweight-and-easy-to-use\">Lightweight and Easy to Use</h3> </div> <p>At around 10KB minified and gzipped, Alpine.js is significantly smaller than many of the other front-end JavaScript frameworks. It&rsquo;s also straightforward to use - if you&rsquo;re familiar with JavaScript and HTML, you&rsquo;ll be able to pick it up quickly.</p> <div class=\"heading-wrapper level-h3\" tabindex=\"-1\"> <h3 id=\"declarative-programming\">Declarative Programming</h3> </div> <p>Alpine.js provides a way of managing state and behavior in a declarative manner, meaning your code describes what should be done, rather than how.</p> <div class=\"heading-wrapper level-h3\" tabindex=\"-1\"> <h3 id=\"versatile\">Versatile</h3> </div> <p>You can use Alpine.js on its own or in combination with other libraries or frameworks. It doesn&rsquo;t dictate your entire front-end structure, making it a perfect choice for adding interactivity to existing projects.</p> <div class=\"heading-wrapper level-h2\" tabindex=\"-1\"> <h2 id=\"getting-started-with-alpinejs\">Getting Started with Alpine.js</h2> </div> <p>To get started, include the script tag in your HTML file:</p> <pre class=\"astro-code github-dark\" tabindex=\"0\" data-language=\"html\"><code><span class=\"line\">&lt;script src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/alpinejs/alpine@v2.x.x/dist/alpine.min.js\" defer&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</span> </code></pre> <p>Alpine.js provides you with a set of directives that you can use within your HTML like so:</p> <pre class=\"astro-code github-dark\" tabindex=\"0\" data-language=\"html\"><code><span class=\"line\">&lt;div x-data=\"{ open: false }\"&gt;</span> <span class=\"line\">    &lt;button @click=\"open = !open\"&gt;Toggle&lt;/button&gt;</span> <span class=\"line\">    &lt;div x-show=\"open\"&gt;</span> <span class=\"line\">        This content will toggle.</span> <span class=\"line\">    &lt;/div&gt;</span> <span class=\"line\">&lt;/div&gt;</span> </code></pre> <p>In this example, when the button is clicked, the&nbsp;<code>open</code>&nbsp;data attribute is toggled, which in turn toggles the visibility of the div below it.</p> <p>Alpine.js brings a refreshing perspective to building interactive user interfaces. It&rsquo;s lightweight, straightforward, and a great choice for adding interactivity to your front-end applications without the weight of a larger framework.</p>"

